      "blocks": {
        "q1": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Is Davines Purifying Shampoo sulfate-free?",
            "content": "<p>Yes. It’s free of harsh sulfates (SLS and SLES) and parabens, and is plant-based, so it clears flakes and soothes the scalp without stripping the hair.</p>"
          }
        },
        "q2": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "title": "What kind of dandruff and scalp concerns is it for?",
            "content": "<p>It’s formulated for both oily and dry dandruff, and for an itchy, flaking scalp. It’s also suitable for sensitive scalps and is often used to help manage seborrheic dermatitis and scalp psoriasis.</p>"
          }
        },
        "q3": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "title": "Is Davines Purifying Shampoo safe for pregnant or breastfeeding women?",
            "content": "<p>Davines products are formulated in line with current cosmetic standards. That said, pregnancy and breastfeeding bring significant changes to the body, so before using this — or any — product during that time, we recommend checking with your gynecologist or doctor.</p>"
          }
        },
        "q4": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "title": "How and how often should I use it?",
            "content": "<p>Apply about a tablespoon to damp hair and scalp and massage it in, focusing on the areas most affected. Leave it on for a few minutes, then rinse thoroughly. For best results, alternate it with Davines Renewing Shampoo or Well-Being Shampoo.</p><p>How often:</p><p>Intensive treatment — twice a week, for a maximum of three weeks.</p><p>Maintenance treatment — once a week for six weeks (you can stop sooner once the problem has cleared up).</p>"
          }
        }
      },
